as an Intracultural Communicative Medium in China -- tPart 3: Commentary -- t9. Intercultural Communication and the Possibility of English as a Lingua Franca -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book investigates the cultural and intercultural aspects of English as a Lingua Franca (ELF). Authors discuss how ‘culture’ and the ‘intercultural’ can be understood, theorised and operationalised in ELF, and how the concepts can be integrated into formats of ELF-oriented learning and teaching. The various cultural connotations are also discussed (ideological, political, religious and historical) and whether it is possible to use and/or teach a lingua franca as if it were culturally neutral. The chapters consider the communication and pedagogical implications of the cultural and intercultural dimensions of ELF and offer suggestions for new directions in ELF research, pedagogy and curriculum development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCross-cultural orientation. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aLanguage and education. 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 0aLingua francas. 0aMulticultural education. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / English as a Second Language.2bisacsh  aEnglish as a lingua franca.  aEnglish language pedagogy.  aIntercultural communication.  aInterculturality.  aLingua franca pedagogies.1 aBaker, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjørge, Anne Kari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByram, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDervin, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDervin, Fred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/